{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4147246f-319e-44ab-af7f-9e0ff905c10b","content":"With **MSTest 3.8.2**, the modern approach is:\n\n- **`TestContext`** — inject via constructor (no more static property).\n- **Sync init** — use the constructor.\n- **Async init** — use `[TestInitialize]` returning `Task`.\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests\n{\n    private readonly HttpClient _client;\n\n    public TestContext TestContext { get; }\n\n    public MyTests(TestContext testContext)\n    {\n        TestContext = testContext;\n        // Synchronous setup\n        _client = new HttpClient();\n    }\n\n    [TestInitialize]\n    public async Task InitializeAsync()\n    {\n        // Async setup (runs before each test)\n        await _client.GetAsync(\"https://example.com/health\");\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public void ExampleTest()\n    {\n        Assert.IsNotNull(TestContext.TestName);\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- Constructor injection of `TestContext` replaced the legacy `public static TestContext` property pattern in MSTest v3.\n- `[TestInitialize]` supports `async Task`, so you don't need workarounds like `.GetAwaiter().GetResult()`.\n- The constructor runs first (sync), then `[TestInitialize]` runs (async) before each test.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"7946a6f8-f432-45f0-b59d-feb993be2055","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"They're using MSTest 3.8.2 on .NET 9.0. In modern MSTest (v3+), the recommended approach is:\n\n1. **TestContext injection**: Use constructor injection (`TestContext` as a constructor parameter) rather than the legacy static property pattern.\n2. **Synchronous init**: Use the constructor.\n3. **Asynchronous init**: Implement `IAsyncInitialization` — wait, that's not MSTest. In MSTest, async init is done via `[TestInitialize]` methods that return `Task`.\n\nActually, let me think about MSTest 3.x specifically:\n\n- `TestContext` can be injected via constructor in MSTest v3+.\n\n\n- `[TestInitialize]` supports `async Task` return type.\n- For synchronous init, use the constructor.\n- For async init, use `[TestInitialize] public async Task InitializeAsync()`.\n\nSo the recommended pattern in modern MSTest 3.x is to inject `TestContext` through the constructor for synchronous setup, then use an async `[TestInitialize]` method for any asynchronous initialization work. I'm clarifying the MSTest v3 approach with constructor injection for `TestContext`, where you can use either synchronous or asynchronous initialization methods depending on your needs.","outputTokens":891},"id":"55160f64-6948-470b-a9b7-e9022cdbaacb","timestamp":"2026-04-03T03:26:50.469Z","parentId":"d4ac8507-40b7-403a-b240-16286529514e"}
